window.MM['oph_p2_squint'] = [
{"q":"A 3-year-old child presents with inward deviation of the right eye since infancy. Cycloplegic refraction reveals +5.50 D hypermetropia in both eyes. The deviation decreases significantly after spectacle correction. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Infantile esotropia","Accommodative esotropia","Sensory esotropia","Paralytic esotropia","Consecutive exotropia"],"a":1,"e":"Accommodative esotropia is strongly associated with uncorrected hypermetropia and usually appears between 2-4 years of age.<br><br>Excessive accommodation stimulates accommodative convergence, producing esodeviation. Cycloplegic correction often markedly reduces or eliminates the deviation.<br><br>Infantile esotropia (A) usually appears before 6 months and is not primarily caused by refractive accommodation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which type of esotropia typically presents before 6 months of age with large-angle deviation?","o":["Accommodative esotropia","Sensory esotropia","Infantile esotropia","Divergence insufficiency","Consecutive esotropia"],"a":2,"e":"Infantile esotropia classically presents before 6 months of age with a large constant angle of deviation.<br><br>Cross-fixation, latent nystagmus, and inferior oblique overaction are frequently associated findings. Onset before six months with a large constant angle is the single most reliable distinguishing feature.<br><br>Accommodative esotropia (A) generally appears later after the development of significant accommodative effort.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with esotropia closes one eye in bright sunlight and demonstrates cross-fixation. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Sensory esotropia","Infantile esotropia","Divergence paralysis","Accommodative spasm","Sixth nerve palsy"],"a":1,"e":"Cross-fixation is a classic feature of infantile esotropia and often mimics bilateral abduction limitation.<br><br>Large-angle constant deviation before 6 months strongly supports the diagnosis.<br><br>Sixth nerve palsy (E) causes true abduction deficit rather than apparent limitation from cross-fixation behavior.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which refractive error is most strongly associated with accommodative esotropia?","o":["Myopia","Hypermetropia","Astigmatism only","Aphakia","Anisocoria"],"a":1,"e":"Hypermetropia is the major refractive association of accommodative esotropia.<br><br>Children accommodate excessively to obtain clear vision, leading to excessive accommodative convergence.<br><br>Myopia (A) usually requires less accommodation for near tasks and therefore is not classically linked to accommodative esodeviation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops esotropia following unilateral dense cataract causing poor vision. Which type of esotropia is most likely?","o":["Infantile esotropia","Accommodative esotropia","Sensory esotropia","Consecutive esotropia","Cyclic esotropia"],"a":2,"e":"Sensory esotropia develops because unilateral visual loss disrupts binocular fusion mechanisms.<br><br>Dense cataract, corneal opacity, or retinal disease may precipitate the deviation.<br><br>Accommodative esotropia (B) is primarily related to hypermetropic accommodative effort rather than sensory deprivation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which muscle is primarily overacting in most cases of esotropia?","o":["Lateral rectus","Inferior rectus","Medial rectus","Superior oblique","Levator palpebrae"],"a":2,"e":"Esotropia results from excessive convergent tone or reduced divergence, with relative medial rectus overaction.<br><br>Many surgical procedures weaken the medial rectus to correct esodeviation. Medial rectus overaction with lateral rectus underaction is the classic motor signature of esotropia.<br><br>Lateral rectus (A) weakness may contribute in paralytic forms but is not the primary muscle overacting.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 4-year-old child with accommodative esotropia has persistent residual deviation despite full hypermetropic correction. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Pure accommodative esotropia","Partially accommodative esotropia","Sensory esotropia","Consecutive exotropia","Divergence insufficiency"],"a":1,"e":"Partially accommodative esotropia demonstrates improvement but incomplete correction after full cycloplegic spectacle prescription.<br><br>Residual deviation may require strabismus surgery.<br><br>Pure accommodative esotropia (A) resolves fully with appropriate hypermetropic correction.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which clinical feature is most strongly associated with infantile esotropia?","o":["Severe hypermetropia","Diplopia","Inferior oblique overaction","Papilledema","Marcus Gunn pupil"],"a":2,"e":"Inferior oblique overaction commonly develops in infantile esotropia.<br><br>Latent nystagmus and dissociated vertical deviation are additional classic associations.<br><br>Diplopia (B) is uncommon in young children because suppression mechanisms develop early.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most important before diagnosing accommodative esotropia?","o":["Gonioscopy","Cycloplegic refraction","Fluorescein angiography","OCT macula","Pachymetry"],"a":1,"e":"Cycloplegic refraction is essential in evaluating childhood esotropia because latent hypermetropia must be accurately measured.<br><br>OCT macula (D) and pachymetry (E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with sixth nerve palsy most commonly develops which deviation?","o":["Exotropia","Hypertropia","Esotropia","Hypotropia","Cyclotropia"],"a":2,"e":"Sixth cranial nerve palsy weakens the lateral rectus muscle, resulting in unopposed medial rectus action and esotropia.<br><br>Horizontal diplopia worsens on gaze toward the affected side.<br><br>Exotropia (A) occurs when the eye deviates outward, usually due to medial rectus weakness or divergence excess.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which type of esotropia may alternate between days of orthotropia and days of esodeviation?","o":["Sensory esotropia","Cyclic esotropia","Accommodative esotropia","Paralytic esotropia","Infantile esotropia"],"a":1,"e":"Cyclic esotropia is a rare condition characterized by alternating periods of normal alignment and esodeviation.<br><br>The cycle classically occurs every 24-48 hours.<br><br>Infantile esotropia (E) usually demonstrates constant large-angle deviation rather than periodic variation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 5-year-old child presents with constant esotropia and suppression of one eye. Which complication is most likely if untreated?","o":["Cataract","Retinal detachment","Amblyopia","Optic neuritis","Papilledema"],"a":2,"e":"Untreated childhood esotropia commonly results in amblyopia because the brain suppresses the deviated eye to avoid diplopia.<br><br>Early detection and management are therefore essential.<br><br>Retinal detachment (B) and optic neuritis (D) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which angle measurement technique is most commonly used in esotropia evaluation?","o":["Schirmer test","Hirschberg test","Gonioscopy","Amsler grid","Tonometry"],"a":1,"e":"The Hirschberg corneal reflex test provides a quick estimate of ocular deviation and is frequently used in pediatric strabismus assessment.<br><br>It is especially useful in uncooperative children.<br><br>Gonioscopy (C) evaluates anterior chamber angle rather than ocular alignment.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with esotropia improves completely after wearing hypermetropic correction. Which management is most appropriate initially?","o":["Immediate surgery","Observation only","Full cycloplegic glasses correction","Enucleation","Corneal transplantation"],"a":2,"e":"Pure accommodative esotropia is primarily managed with full cycloplegic hypermetropic correction.<br><br>Many children achieve satisfactory ocular alignment without surgery.<br><br>Immediate surgery (A) is unnecessary if spectacles fully control the deviation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which condition is commonly associated with dissociated vertical deviation?","o":["Accommodative esotropia","Infantile esotropia","Divergence insufficiency","Myopia","Thyroid eye disease"],"a":1,"e":"Dissociated vertical deviation is classically associated with infantile esotropia and often appears later during childhood.<br><br>Latent nystagmus and inferior oblique overaction are additional common associations.<br><br>Accommodative esotropia (A) is more strongly linked with hypermetropia rather than dissociated vertical deviation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops acute painful diplopia with inability to abduct the eye. Which nerve is most likely involved?","o":["Oculomotor nerve","Trochlear nerve","Abducens nerve","Optic nerve","Facial nerve"],"a":2,"e":"Abducens nerve palsy produces lateral rectus weakness, causing esotropia and horizontal diplopia worse on gaze toward the affected side.<br><br>Patients often adopt a compensatory head turn.<br><br>Trochlear nerve palsy (B) primarily causes vertical diplopia rather than esodeviation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which age group most commonly presents with accommodative esotropia?","o":["Neonates before 3 months","2-4 years","Adolescents only","Elderly patients","Premature infants exclusively"],"a":1,"e":"Accommodative esotropia most commonly presents between 2-4 years of age when accommodative demand increases.<br><br>Hypermetropia is the key associated refractive error.<br><br>Infantile esotropia (A) presents earlier, usually before 6 months.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which condition may mimic bilateral sixth nerve palsy because of cross-fixation?","o":["Accommodative esotropia","Infantile esotropia","Divergence paralysis","Sensory exotropia","Myasthenia gravis"],"a":1,"e":"Cross-fixation in infantile esotropia can create apparent bilateral abduction limitation, mimicking sixth nerve palsy.<br><br>True sixth nerve palsy demonstrates genuine lateral rectus weakness.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which type of esotropia is most likely in an elderly patient with binocular diplopia worse at distance and normal near alignment?","o":["Accommodative esotropia","Divergence insufficiency esotropia","Infantile esotropia","Sensory esotropia","Consecutive exotropia"],"a":1,"e":"Divergence insufficiency esotropia typically occurs in older adults and produces esodeviation greater at distance than near.<br><br>Patients complain mainly of horizontal diplopia for distant targets.<br><br>Accommodative esotropia (A) is a pediatric hypermetropic condition.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which statement regarding infantile esotropia is most accurate?","o":["It usually begins after 7 years of age","Diplopia is the dominant symptom","It commonly presents before 6 months of age","Hypermetropia is always severe","It resolves spontaneously in most patients"],"a":2,"e":"Infantile esotropia classically presents before 6 months with large-angle constant deviation.<br><br>Associated findings include cross-fixation, latent nystagmus, dissociated vertical deviation, and inferior oblique overaction.<br><br>Diplopia is uncommon because suppression develops early in infancy. Hypermetropia is usually mild rather than markedly high.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 9-year-old child is brought with outward drifting of the left eye noticed mainly during daydreaming, fatigue, and exposure to bright sunlight. Teachers report that the child intermittently loses focus while looking at the classroom board. The mother also notices that the child closes one eye outdoors in sunlight. Visual acuity is normal in both eyes, and ocular movements are full. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Infantile esotropia","Intermittent exotropia","Sixth nerve palsy","Accommodative esotropia","Duane syndrome"],"a":1,"e":"Intermittent exotropia is the commonest type of exotropia in children and frequently worsens with fatigue, inattention, or bright light exposure. The deviation is usually intermittent initially, with good binocular control between episodes.<br><br>Infantile esotropia (A) causes convergent deviation before 6 months of age. Sixth nerve palsy (C) produces abduction limitation and esotropia rather than outward deviation. Accommodative esotropia (D) is associated with hypermetropia and inward turning. Duane syndrome (E) demonstrates globe retraction and restricted movements.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which type of exotropia is most commonly encountered in pediatric ophthalmology clinics and frequently discussed in FCPS Part 1 recall collections?","o":["Constant exotropia","Sensory exotropia","Intermittent exotropia","Paralytic exotropia","Consecutive exotropia"],"a":2,"e":"Intermittent exotropia is the most frequently encountered exodeviation in clinical ophthalmology practice. Children typically maintain fusion for much of the day, but the eye drifts outward during fatigue, illness, or reduced attention. Good stereopsis may persist in early stages.<br><br>Constant exotropia (A) shows persistent manifest deviation without periods of control. Sensory exotropia (B) occurs secondary to poor unilateral vision. Paralytic exotropia (D) usually results from cranial nerve palsies. Consecutive exotropia (E) develops after prior esotropia correction or surgery.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 12-year-old student complains of outward drifting of the eyes mainly while looking at distant objects in school. Near tasks remain relatively unaffected. Cover testing demonstrates a significantly larger exodeviation at distance fixation compared with near fixation. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Convergence insufficiency exotropia","Divergence excess exotropia","Sensory exotropia","Infantile exotropia","Restrictive exotropia"],"a":1,"e":"Divergence excess exotropia is characterized by a greater exodeviation at distance than at near fixation. Patients often maintain excellent near fusion and stereopsis but struggle with distance alignment, particularly during fatigue or inattention.<br><br>Convergence insufficiency exotropia (A) demonstrates greater deviation at near fixation with reading difficulty. Sensory exotropia (C) results from reduced visual acuity. Infantile exotropia (D) presents very early in life. Restrictive exotropia (E) is associated with mechanical limitation of ocular movements.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 15-year-old teenager complains of headaches, asthenopia, and intermittent diplopia during prolonged reading sessions. Examination reveals exodeviation significantly greater at near fixation than at distance. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Divergence excess exotropia","Consecutive exotropia","Sensory exotropia","Paralytic exotropia","Convergence insufficiency exotropia"],"a":4,"e":"Convergence insufficiency exotropia commonly presents with headaches, asthenopia, and difficulty maintaining binocular single vision during prolonged near tasks. Near exodeviation exceeds distance deviation, making reading particularly symptomatic.<br><br>Divergence excess exotropia (A) shows larger deviation at distance fixation. Sensory exotropia (C) occurs due to unilateral visual impairment. Paralytic exotropia (D) is associated with extraocular muscle palsy and diplopia in specific gazes. Consecutive exotropia (B) follows previous esotropia treatment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 54-year-old diabetic patient develops acute horizontal diplopia and outward deviation of the right eye. Examination reveals ptosis, impaired adduction, impaired elevation, and a \"down and out\" ocular posture. Which cranial nerve is most likely affected?","o":["Fourth cranial nerve","Sixth cranial nerve","Third cranial nerve","Optic nerve","Facial nerve"],"a":2,"e":"Third cranial nerve palsy produces exotropia because the lateral rectus and superior oblique muscles act unopposed. Patients classically demonstrate ptosis with a \"down and out\" eye position. Pupillary involvement may suggest compressive pathology such as aneurysm.<br><br>Sixth nerve palsy (B) causes esotropia due to lateral rectus weakness. Fourth nerve palsy (A) mainly produces vertical diplopia and hypertropia. Optic nerve lesions (D) reduce vision without causing characteristic ocular deviation. Facial nerve palsy (E) affects eyelid closure rather than ocular alignment.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with intermittent exotropia maintains good stereopsis and binocular fusion between episodes of manifest deviation. Which statement best explains this finding?","o":["Presence of restrictive strabismus","Optic nerve disease","Advanced amblyopia","Preserved binocular sensory function","Retinal pathology"],"a":3,"e":"Children with intermittent exotropia often retain excellent binocular fusion and stereopsis during periods when ocular alignment is controlled. This preserved sensory status explains why many patients remain asymptomatic early in the disease course. Loss of control may gradually occur over time.<br><br>Restrictive strabismus (A) limits ocular movement mechanically. Advanced amblyopia (C) reduces binocular potential rather than preserving it. Optic nerve disease (B) and retinal pathology (E) primarily affect visual acuity rather than producing intermittent fusion control abnormalities.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops persistent outward deviation of one eye several years after surgery for congenital esotropia. Which term best describes this postoperative complication?","o":["Sensory exotropia","Paralytic exotropia","Infantile exotropia","Consecutive exotropia","Divergence excess exotropia"],"a":3,"e":"Consecutive exotropia refers to exodeviation developing after treatment or surgical correction of esotropia. Overcorrection during medial rectus weakening procedures is a common mechanism. The condition may appear immediately postoperatively or years later.<br><br>Sensory exotropia (A) occurs because of poor vision and disrupted fusion. Infantile exotropia (C) presents early in infancy rather than after surgery. Paralytic exotropia (B) results from cranial nerve palsy. Divergence excess exotropia (E) mainly affects distance fixation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 17-year-old patient with unilateral dense traumatic cataract gradually develops outward deviation of the affected eye. Visual acuity is markedly reduced in the involved eye. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Intermittent exotropia","Divergence excess exotropia","Sensory exotropia","Infantile exotropia","Cyclic exotropia"],"a":2,"e":"Sensory exotropia develops when unilateral visual impairment disrupts binocular fusion mechanisms. Cataract, corneal opacity, retinal disease, or optic atrophy may precipitate the deviation. Older children and adults with longstanding poor vision commonly develop outward deviation.<br><br>Intermittent exotropia (A) usually occurs in patients with relatively normal vision and preserved fusion. Divergence excess exotropia (B) mainly affects distance alignment. Infantile exotropia (D) presents early in infancy. Cyclic exotropia (E) alternates periodically between alignment and deviation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most useful for evaluating suppression and binocular fusion in patients with intermittent exotropia?","o":["Worth four-dot test","Schirmer test","Gonioscopy","Fluorescein angiography","OCT macula"],"a":0,"e":"Worth four-dot testing is commonly used to assess suppression, fusion, and binocular sensory status in strabismus patients. Patients with intermittent exotropia often suppress one eye intermittently to avoid diplopia during manifest deviation episodes.<br><br>Schirmer test (B) evaluates tear secretion. Gonioscopy (C) examines the anterior chamber angle. Fluorescein angiography (D) studies retinal vasculature, while OCT macula (E) evaluates retinal morphology rather than binocular sensory function.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with intermittent exotropia is brought because the parents notice worsening outward drifting over the last year. The deviation now appears more frequently and remains manifest for longer periods. Which statement regarding disease progression is most accurate?","o":["Intermittent exotropia always resolves spontaneously","Diplopia is always absent","Severe amblyopia is inevitable","Control may deteriorate gradually over time","Surgery is never required"],"a":3,"e":"Intermittent exotropia may progress gradually from well-controlled intermittent deviation to poorly controlled or constant exotropia. Increasing frequency and duration of manifest deviation are important indicators of deteriorating control and possible need for intervention.<br><br>Severe amblyopia (C) is less common than in esotropia because alternating fixation often develops. Diplopia (B) may occur in older children or adults. Surgery (E) may become necessary if control worsens significantly or binocular function declines.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 10-year-old child is brought because the right eye drifts outward mainly while watching television or staring into the distance. The deviation becomes more obvious during fatigue and illness, but near vision remains relatively controlled. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Divergence excess exotropia","Sensory exotropia","Convergence insufficiency exotropia","Consecutive exotropia","Restrictive exotropia"],"a":0,"e":"Divergence excess exotropia is characterized by greater exodeviation at distance fixation compared with near fixation. Children often maintain good near fusion but lose control while looking at distant targets, particularly during fatigue or daydreaming.<br><br>It represents one of the commonest intermittent exotropia subtypes encountered clinically. Good stereopsis may remain preserved in early stages.<br><br>Convergence insufficiency exotropia (C) causes larger near deviation. Sensory exotropia (B) occurs due to unilateral visual loss. Consecutive exotropia (D) follows esotropia treatment. Restrictive exotropia (E) is associated with motility limitation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A teenager complains of headaches, eye strain, and intermittent diplopia while reading for long periods. Examination reveals exotropia significantly greater at near fixation than at distance. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Divergence excess exotropia","Paralytic exotropia","Sensory exotropia","Infantile exotropia","Convergence insufficiency exotropia"],"a":4,"e":"Convergence insufficiency exotropia typically presents with asthenopia, reading difficulty, and near diplopia. Near exodeviation exceeds distance deviation because of inadequate convergence during prolonged close work.<br><br>The condition is particularly common among adolescents and young adults performing sustained near tasks.<br><br>Divergence excess exotropia (A) mainly affects distance fixation. Paralytic exotropia (B) demonstrates extraocular muscle weakness. Infantile exotropia (D) presents early in life. Sensory exotropia (C) results from poor unilateral vision.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops outward deviation of the left eye several years after successful surgery for congenital esotropia. Which term best describes this condition?","o":["Intermittent exotropia","Paralytic exotropia","Sensory exotropia","Cyclic exotropia","Consecutive exotropia"],"a":4,"e":"Consecutive exotropia refers to exodeviation developing after previous correction or surgery for esotropia. It may occur immediately postoperatively or appear years later due to overcorrection or gradual change in ocular alignment.<br><br>This condition is highly tested in surgical strabismus discussions because management often requires careful reassessment and possible reoperation. Prism cover testing is essential before intervention.<br><br>Intermittent exotropia (A) develops independently without prior esotropia treatment. Sensory exotropia (C) occurs secondary to visual loss. Cyclic exotropia (D) alternates periodically. Paralytic exotropia (B) is neurogenic.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 40-year-old patient with unilateral dense traumatic cataract develops progressive outward deviation of the affected eye over several years. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Divergence excess exotropia","Sensory exotropia","Infantile exotropia","Convergence insufficiency","Cyclic exotropia"],"a":1,"e":"Sensory exotropia develops when poor visual acuity disrupts binocular fusion mechanisms. Dense cataract, retinal disease, corneal opacity, or optic atrophy commonly precipitate the deviation, particularly in older children and adults.<br><br>Loss of fusion leads the eye to drift outward gradually.<br><br>Divergence excess exotropia (A) occurs in patients with preserved vision. Infantile exotropia (C) presents very early in life. Convergence insufficiency (D) mainly affects near fixation. Cyclic exotropia (E) occurs periodically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with intermittent exotropia closes one eye when exposed to bright sunlight. What is the most likely explanation for this phenomenon?","o":["Breakdown of fusional control","Corneal edema","Acute glaucoma","Papilledema","Optic neuritis"],"a":0,"e":"Bright sunlight may disrupt binocular fusion and suppression mechanisms in intermittent exotropia, causing manifest deviation and prompting monocular eye closure.<br><br>Children often demonstrate normal binocular alignment indoors but lose control outdoors in intense illumination. The symptom may precede progression to more frequent manifest deviation.<br><br>Corneal edema (B) and acute glaucoma (C) cause painful photophobia. Papilledema (D) affects optic nerve function. Optic neuritis (E) primarily causes painful visual loss rather than intermittent eye closure.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which cranial nerve palsy most commonly produces exotropia associated with ptosis and a \"down and out\" eye position?","o":["Third cranial nerve palsy","Sixth cranial nerve palsy","Fourth cranial nerve palsy","Facial nerve palsy","Optic nerve lesion"],"a":0,"e":"Third cranial nerve palsy weakens the medial rectus, superior rectus, inferior rectus, and inferior oblique muscles, leaving lateral rectus and superior oblique action unopposed. The eye therefore assumes a characteristic \"down and out\" position with exotropia.<br><br>Associated ptosis and pupillary involvement are important clinical findings. Aneurysmal compression must always be excluded in painful pupil-involving third nerve palsy. Third nerve palsy producing a down-and-out eye with ptosis is a frequently confused emergency presentation.<br><br>Fourth nerve palsy (C) mainly causes vertical diplopia. Sixth nerve palsy (B) produces esotropia. Facial nerve palsy (D) affects eyelid closure. Optic nerve lesions (E) reduce vision without characteristic strabismus posture.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with intermittent exotropia demonstrates excellent stereopsis and binocular fusion between episodes of ocular deviation. What does this finding suggest?","o":["Poor visual prognosis","Optic nerve dysfunction","Restrictive strabismus","Advanced amblyopia","Preserved binocular sensory function"],"a":4,"e":"Intermittent exotropia often preserves normal stereopsis and binocular sensory fusion during periods of ocular alignment. Good stereopsis indicates intact cortical binocular processing and generally predicts favorable postoperative functional outcomes.<br><br>Maintained binocular function differentiates intermittent exotropia from longstanding constant deviations associated with deep suppression and amblyopia.<br><br>Restrictive strabismus (C) affects ocular motility mechanically. Advanced amblyopia (D) reduces stereopsis significantly. Optic nerve dysfunction (B) primarily impairs visual acuity and fields rather than preserving binocular function.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most useful for evaluating suppression in a patient with intermittent exotropia?","o":["Worth four-dot test","Gonioscopy","OCT macula","Pachymetry","Keratometry"],"a":0,"e":"Worth four-dot testing evaluates binocular fusion, diplopia, and suppression using red-green filters and illuminated targets. Patients with intermittent exotropia frequently suppress one eye during manifest deviation to avoid diplopia.<br><br>The investigation is rapid, inexpensive, and highly valuable in orthoptic assessment.<br><br>Gonioscopy (B) assesses anterior chamber angle anatomy. OCT macula (C) evaluates retinal structure. Pachymetry (D) measures corneal thickness. Keratometry (E) measures corneal curvature rather than binocular sensory function.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which extraocular muscle is functionally underacting in most forms of exotropia?","o":["Lateral rectus","Superior oblique","Inferior rectus","Medial rectus","Superior rectus"],"a":3,"e":"Exotropia generally reflects deficient convergence or relative weakness of medial rectus function compared with lateral rectus activity. Many surgical procedures therefore strengthen the medial rectus or weaken the lateral rectus muscles.<br><br>Understanding extraocular muscle balance is fundamental in planning strabismus surgery and interpreting ocular deviation patterns clinically.<br><br>Lateral rectus weakness (A) more commonly causes esotropia. Superior oblique (B), inferior rectus (C), and superior rectus (E) dysfunction primarily produce vertical or torsional deviations rather than classic exotropia.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with intermittent exotropia is followed regularly. Over time, the parents notice increasing frequency and duration of manifest outward deviation. Which statement regarding disease progression is most accurate?","o":["Intermittent exotropia always resolves spontaneously","Surgery is contraindicated","Severe amblyopia is inevitable","Diplopia never occurs","Control may deteriorate gradually with time"],"a":4,"e":"Intermittent exotropia may progress gradually from well-controlled intermittent deviation to poorly controlled or constant exotropia. Increasing frequency of manifest deviation indicates declining fusional control and possible need for intervention.<br><br>Patients initially maintain excellent binocular vision, but deterioration can reduce stereopsis and affect psychosocial functioning. Monitoring progression is therefore essential during follow-up.<br><br>Severe amblyopia (C) is less common because alternating fixation often develops. Diplopia (D) may occur in older children and adults. Surgery (B) is indicated when control deteriorates significantly.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A 5-year-old child is brought for evaluation of intermittent outward deviation of the right eye. The ophthalmologist alternately covers each eye while observing movement of the fellow eye to determine the presence and direction of manifest strabismus. Which test is being performed?","o":["Hirschberg test","Prism bar cover test","Worth four-dot test","Cover-uncover test","Maddox rod test"],"a":3,"e":"The cover-uncover test is the basic clinical method used to detect manifest squint (tropia). While one eye is occluded, fixation movement of the uncovered eye indicates the presence and direction of ocular deviation.<br><br>The test is especially valuable in pediatric patients because it quickly differentiates manifest strabismus from latent deviation. Accurate performance requires stable fixation and careful observation of ocular movements during alternate occlusion.<br><br>Hirschberg test (A) only estimates deviation roughly using corneal reflexes. Prism cover test (B) measures angle quantitatively. Worth four-dot test (C) evaluates suppression and fusion. Maddox rod test (E) mainly assesses diplopia and heterophoria.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is considered the gold standard for accurate quantification of squint angle in cooperative patients?","o":["Prism cover test","Synoptophore","Hirschberg test","Maddox wing","Bagolini glasses"],"a":0,"e":"The prism cover test is considered the most accurate clinical method for quantifying ocular deviation. Increasing prism strength neutralizes ocular movement during alternate cover testing, allowing precise measurement of strabismus angle.<br><br>The test is particularly important in surgical planning and monitoring postoperative alignment. Accurate measurements require patient cooperation and stable fixation throughout examination. Both near and distance deviations can be assessed effectively.<br><br>Hirschberg test (C) provides only approximate estimation. Synoptophore (B) evaluates fusion and retinal correspondence. Maddox wing (D) mainly measures near heterophoria. Bagolini glasses (E) assess sensory fusion rather than deviation magnitude.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with intermittent exotropia undergoes a test using red and green lights to evaluate suppression and binocular fusion. Which test is most likely being performed?","o":["Worth four-dot test","Hess chart","Lancaster test","Amsler grid","Ishihara test"],"a":0,"e":"Worth four-dot testing evaluates binocular single vision, suppression, and diplopia using red-green goggles and illuminated dots. Children with intermittent exotropia often suppress one eye during manifest deviation to avoid diplopia. This is a highly recalled FCPS orthoptic investigation.<br><br>The patient's response determines whether binocular fusion, suppression, or diplopia is present. The test is simple, rapid, and useful in both children and adults with sensory strabismus abnormalities.<br><br>Hess chart (B) and Lancaster test (C) evaluate extraocular muscle palsies. Amsler grid (D) assesses macular pathology. Ishihara testing (E) evaluates color vision defects rather than binocular sensory status.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which bedside test provides a rough estimation of ocular deviation based on corneal light reflex position?","o":["Prism adaptation test","Worth four-dot test","Synoptophore","Maddox rod test","Hirschberg test"],"a":4,"e":"The Hirschberg test estimates ocular deviation by observing displacement of the corneal light reflex from the pupillary center. It is especially useful in infants and uncooperative children where formal prism testing cannot be performed reliably.<br><br>Approximately 1 mm displacement of the corneal reflex corresponds to about 7 degrees or 15 prism diopters of deviation.<br><br>Prism adaptation test (A) is used for surgical planning in selected strabismus cases. Synoptophore (C) studies binocular vision. Maddox rod test (D) evaluates diplopia. Worth four-dot test (B) assesses suppression and fusion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient complains of horizontal diplopia worse on left gaze. Hess charting is performed. What is the primary purpose of Hess chart testing?","o":["Measuring intraocular pressure","Evaluating retinal function","Assessing extraocular muscle palsy","Detecting amblyopia","Measuring refractive error"],"a":2,"e":"Hess charting evaluates ocular motility disturbances and identifies paretic extraocular muscles. The affected muscle demonstrates a reduced field of action, while the contralateral synergist shows secondary overaction according to Hering's law.<br><br>The test is particularly useful in paralytic squints and helps differentiate neurogenic palsies from restrictive disorders.<br><br>Intraocular pressure (A) is measured with tonometry. Retinal function (B) requires electrophysiological testing. Amblyopia detection (D) depends mainly on visual acuity testing. Refractive error measurement (E) requires retinoscopy or refraction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most important before diagnosing accommodative esotropia in a child?","o":["Gonioscopy","Pachymetry","OCT macula","Cycloplegic refraction","ERG"],"a":3,"e":"Cycloplegic refraction is essential in children with suspected accommodative esotropia because latent hypermetropia must be measured accurately. Excessive accommodative effort in uncorrected hypermetropia produces convergent deviation through accommodative convergence mechanisms.<br><br>Atropine or cyclopentolate is commonly used to achieve cycloplegia.<br><br>Gonioscopy (A) evaluates the anterior chamber angle. OCT macula (C) assesses retinal structure. Pachymetry (B) measures corneal thickness. ERG (E) evaluates retinal electrophysiological function rather than refractive accommodative status.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with suspected amblyopia due to esotropia undergoes visual acuity assessment using symbols rather than letters. Which chart is most suitable?","o":["Snellen chart","Jaeger chart","Hess chart","Amsler grid","Lea symbols chart"],"a":4,"e":"Lea symbols charts are designed for young children who cannot reliably identify alphabetic letters. They use recognizable symbols such as circles, houses, apples, and squares to assess visual acuity accurately in pediatric patients.<br><br>Early amblyopia detection depends on age-appropriate visual acuity testing.<br><br>Snellen chart (A) requires letter recognition. Jaeger chart (B) measures near vision. Amsler grid (D) assesses macular disease. Hess chart (C) evaluates ocular motility rather than visual acuity.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is specifically designed to evaluate binocular fusion and stereopsis therapeutically and diagnostically?","o":["Synoptophore","Retinoscopy","Schiotz tonometry","Keratometry","Gonioscopy"],"a":0,"e":"The synoptophore evaluates binocular sensory and motor fusion, retinal correspondence, suppression, and stereopsis. It is an important orthoptic instrument used both diagnostically and therapeutically in strabismus management.<br><br>Separate images are presented to each eye while alignment and fusion ability are assessed.<br><br>Retinoscopy (B) measures refractive error. Schiotz tonometry (C) measures intraocular pressure. Keratometry (D) measures corneal curvature. Gonioscopy (E) evaluates anterior chamber angle structures rather than binocular vision.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with suspected superior oblique palsy undergoes a test involving head tilting to each shoulder. Which test is being performed?","o":["Bruckner test","Bielschowsky head tilt test","Maddox wing test","Krimsky test","Worth four-dot test"],"a":1,"e":"The Bielschowsky head tilt test is classically used to diagnose superior oblique palsy. Hypertropia increases when the patient tilts the head toward the affected side because the paretic superior oblique cannot intort the eye properly.<br><br>The test is highly valuable in differentiating vertical muscle palsies.<br><br>Bruckner test (A) screens for strabismus and anisometropia. Maddox wing test (C) measures near heterophoria. Krimsky test (D) estimates deviation using prisms. Worth four-dot test (E) evaluates fusion and suppression.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 7-year-old child with partially accommodative esotropia is planned for strabismus surgery. Before surgery, the ophthalmologist places increasing prisms over the spectacles for several weeks to determine the full latent deviation. Which investigation or procedure is being performed?","o":["Hess charting","Krimsky test","Maddox rod test","Prism adaptation test","Synoptophore training"],"a":3,"e":"The prism adaptation test is used before strabismus surgery to uncover the full angle of deviation and improve surgical planning accuracy. Increasing prism power neutralizes fusional effort, allowing the surgeon to detect latent components of esodeviation.<br><br>This test is especially important in partially accommodative esotropia because inadequate preoperative assessment may result in undercorrection or postoperative residual deviation.<br><br>Hess charting (A) evaluates paralytic squints. Maddox rod test (C) assesses diplopia subjectively. Krimsky test (B) estimates deviation in uncooperative children. Synoptophore (E) mainly evaluates binocular sensory fusion rather than surgical prism adaptation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 35-year-old patient presents after orbital trauma with vertical diplopia worse on upgaze. Forced duction testing is performed under topical anesthesia before surgery. What is the primary purpose of this test?","o":["Measuring retinal correspondence","Detecting refractive error","Differentiating restrictive from paralytic squint","Measuring stereopsis","Evaluating suppression"],"a":2,"e":"Forced duction testing helps differentiate restrictive ocular motility disorders from neurogenic muscle palsies. Mechanical resistance during passive ocular movement indicates restrictive pathology such as muscle entrapment after orbital fracture.<br><br>This investigation is highly important in orbital trauma because entrapment requires urgent surgical intervention to prevent persistent diplopia and muscle ischemia.<br><br>Retinal correspondence (A) is assessed by synoptophore. Refractive error (B) requires refraction testing. Stereopsis (D) is evaluated with Titmus testing. Suppression (E) is commonly assessed using Worth four-dot testing.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient develops persistent diplopia after strabismus surgery. Lancaster red-green testing is ordered. What information does this investigation primarily provide?","o":["Corneal thickness","Retinal vascular status","Tear film stability","Macular function","Ocular muscle imbalance mapping"],"a":4,"e":"Lancaster red-green testing maps diplopia fields and identifies ocular muscle imbalance in patients with paralytic or postoperative strabismus. Separate red and green targets are compared to identify underacting and overacting muscles precisely.<br><br>The investigation is particularly valuable after strabismus surgery because subtle incomitance or residual muscle imbalance may not be obvious on simple ocular motility examination alone. Diplopia charting after strabismus surgery is a classic scenario distinguishing overcorrection from muscle slippage.<br><br>Corneal thickness (A) is measured by pachymetry. Retinal vasculature (B) requires fluorescein angiography. Macular function (D) is assessed with OCT or Amsler grid. Tear film stability (C) is evaluated separately.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with intermittent exotropia demonstrates excellent stereopsis on Titmus fly testing before surgery. What does this finding most strongly indicate?","o":["Advanced amblyopia","Poor binocular potential","Optic nerve disease","Restrictive strabismus","Preserved binocular fusion"],"a":4,"e":"Good stereopsis on Titmus fly testing indicates preserved binocular sensory function and fusion. Patients with intermittent exotropia often maintain normal stereopsis between episodes of manifest deviation, particularly in early disease stages.<br><br>Preserved stereopsis is an important prognostic factor when considering surgery because patients with intact binocular potential generally achieve better postoperative functional outcomes.<br><br>Advanced amblyopia (A) reduces stereopsis markedly. Restrictive strabismus (D) primarily affects ocular motility mechanically. Optic nerve disease (C) affects visual acuity and fields rather than directly preserving stereopsis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"During evaluation of a child for medial rectus recession surgery, alternate cover testing demonstrates latent deviation only after fusion is interrupted completely. What condition is being identified?","o":["Manifest tropia","Dissociated vertical deviation","Nystagmus","Cyclotropia","Heterophoria"],"a":4,"e":"Heterophoria is a latent ocular deviation controlled by binocular fusion under normal circumstances. The alternate cover test disrupts fusion completely, allowing the latent deviation to become apparent during refixation movement.<br><br>Detecting associated heterophoria before surgery is clinically important because unrecognized latent deviations may influence postoperative ocular alignment and patient symptoms.<br><br>Manifest tropia (A) is visible even without dissociation. Nystagmus (C) consists of rhythmic oscillatory eye movements. Cyclotropia (D) involves torsional misalignment. Dissociated vertical deviation (B) represents vertical drifting unrelated to heterophoria.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient undergoing evaluation for restrictive thyroid eye disease has forced duction testing showing marked resistance to passive elevation. Which muscle is most commonly involved?","o":["Superior oblique","Lateral rectus","Inferior rectus","Medial rectus","Superior rectus"],"a":2,"e":"Inferior rectus restriction is the most common extraocular muscle involvement in thyroid eye disease. Resistance to passive elevation during forced duction testing strongly suggests restrictive pathology rather than neurogenic weakness.<br><br>This finding is surgically important because restrictive strabismus due to thyroid ophthalmopathy may require muscle recession procedures after inflammatory stabilization.<br><br>Superior oblique (A) involvement is less common. Lateral rectus (B) and medial rectus (D) may be involved later. Superior rectus (E) restriction is comparatively uncommon in thyroid-associated orbitopathy.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with congenital esotropia is being evaluated before bilateral medial rectus recession surgery. Which investigation is most important for identifying amblyopia preoperatively?","o":["Cycloplegic refraction with visual acuity assessment","Gonioscopy","Corneal pachymetry","OCT RNFL","Fluorescein angiography"],"a":0,"e":"Cycloplegic refraction combined with age-appropriate visual acuity testing is essential before strabismus surgery to identify amblyopia and significant refractive errors. Treating amblyopia preoperatively improves surgical outcomes and binocular development.<br><br>Children with congenital esotropia frequently have fixation preference or suppression leading to amblyopia if not recognized early.<br><br>Gonioscopy (B) evaluates the anterior chamber angle. Pachymetry (C) measures corneal thickness. OCT RNFL (D) assesses optic nerve fibers. Fluorescein angiography (E) evaluates retinal vasculature.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient complains of torsional diplopia after head trauma. Maddox rod testing reveals image tilting. Which cranial nerve palsy is most likely responsible?","o":["Third cranial nerve palsy","Fourth cranial nerve palsy","Sixth cranial nerve palsy","Optic nerve lesion","Facial nerve palsy"],"a":1,"e":"Fourth cranial nerve palsy classically causes torsional diplopia because the superior oblique muscle is responsible for intorsion of the eye. Maddox rod testing is useful for identifying subjective torsional imbalance.<br><br>Patients often adopt compensatory head tilt away from the affected side to minimize diplopia. Trauma is a common acquired cause of trochlear nerve palsy.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) mainly produces ptosis and exotropia. Sixth nerve palsy (C) causes horizontal diplopia with esotropia. Optic nerve lesions (D) reduce vision rather than causing torsional diplopia.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with long-standing exotropia undergoes Worth four-dot testing and sees only two red dots. What does this finding indicate?","o":["Normal binocular fusion","Diplopia","Cyclotropia","Restrictive strabismus","Suppression of the left eye"],"a":4,"e":"Seeing only two red dots during Worth four-dot testing indicates suppression of the eye viewing through the green filter. Suppression develops to eliminate diplopia and confusion in longstanding strabismus patients.<br><br>The test remains one of the simplest and highest-yield methods for assessing binocular sensory status in orthoptic practice and postgraduate ophthalmology recalls. A long-standing exotrope showing fusion on Worth four-dot at near but suppression at distance is a hallmark pattern.<br><br>Normal fusion (A) produces perception of four dots. Diplopia (B) results in five dots. Restrictive strabismus (D) affects motility mechanically. Cyclotropia (C) involves torsional deviation rather than suppression findings.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient planned for strabismus surgery undergoes synoptophore evaluation demonstrating abnormal retinal correspondence. Why is this investigation clinically important preoperatively?","o":["It measures intraocular pressure","It evaluates retinal tears","It detects glaucoma","It predicts postoperative binocular sensory outcome","It measures corneal curvature"],"a":3,"e":"Synoptophore assessment of retinal correspondence helps predict binocular sensory outcomes after strabismus surgery. Abnormal retinal correspondence may limit restoration of normal binocular single vision despite satisfactory cosmetic alignment.<br><br>Preoperative sensory evaluation is therefore important in longstanding childhood squints and adult strabismus cases before surgical correction is planned.<br><br>Intraocular pressure (A) is measured by tonometry. Retinal tears (B) require fundus examination. Corneal curvature (E) is measured using keratometry. Glaucoma detection (C) depends on optic nerve and pressure assessment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with postoperative consecutive exotropia undergoes prism cover testing revealing a 35-prism diopter deviation. Why is accurate prism quantification essential before reoperation?","o":["To diagnose cataract","To assess tear production","To evaluate retinal vascularization","To determine precise surgical dosage","To diagnose keratoconus"],"a":3,"e":"Accurate prism cover testing is essential before repeat strabismus surgery because surgical dosage depends directly on deviation magnitude. Underestimation or overestimation may result in persistent deviation or overcorrection.<br><br>Consecutive exotropia after previous esotropia surgery requires particularly careful preoperative measurements because scar tissue and altered muscle dynamics complicate surgical planning.<br><br>Cataract diagnosis (A) depends on slit-lamp examination. Tear production (B) is assessed by Schirmer testing. Retinal vascularization (C) requires angiography. Keratoconus (E) is evaluated using corneal topography.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 6-year-old child is brought with suspected squint. During examination, the corneal light reflex is centered in the left pupil but lies at the temporal pupillary margin in the right eye. Which type of deviation is most likely present?","o":["Exotropia","Cyclotropia","Hypertropia","Esotropia","Orthophoria"],"a":3,"e":"In the Hirschberg test, temporal displacement of the corneal light reflex indicates inward deviation of the eye, consistent with esotropia. The test is particularly useful in children who cannot cooperate for formal prism cover testing.<br><br>Approximately 1 mm of corneal reflex displacement corresponds to nearly 15 prism diopters of deviation. This bedside method remains one of the most commonly used screening examinations in pediatric strabismus clinics.<br><br>Exotropia (A) causes nasal displacement of the reflex. Hypertropia (C) produces vertical displacement. Cyclotropia (B) involves torsional rotation rather than horizontal misalignment. Orthophoria (E) demonstrates symmetrical central corneal reflexes.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"During alternate cover testing, the right eye moves inward to refixate when uncovered. What does this finding indicate?","o":["Esotropia of the right eye","Cyclophoria","Left hypertropia","Orthophoria","Exotropia of the right eye"],"a":4,"e":"When the uncovered eye moves inward to regain fixation during cover testing, the eye was previously deviated outward, indicating exotropia. Refixation movement direction helps determine the type of deviation accurately.<br><br>Alternate cover testing disrupts fusion completely and reveals both latent and manifest ocular deviations.<br><br>Esotropia (A) produces outward refixation movement. Hypertropia (C) causes vertical corrective movement. Orthophoria (D) shows no refixation movement. Cyclophoria (B) involves torsional misalignment not detected this way.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with suspected amblyopia undergoes fixation testing. The examiner notes that the child consistently prefers fixation with the left eye. What does this finding most strongly suggest?","o":["Bilateral amblyopia","Equal visual acuity","Nystagmus","Papilledema","Right eye amblyopia"],"a":4,"e":"Persistent fixation preference for one eye in childhood strabismus strongly suggests reduced visual acuity in the nonpreferred eye, commonly due to amblyopia. Fixation behavior is especially valuable in preverbal children unable to perform visual acuity charts.<br><br>Children naturally prefer the eye providing clearer vision. Early identification of fixation preference is critical because untreated amblyopia may become irreversible after visual maturation.<br><br>Bilateral amblyopia (A) usually lacks strong unilateral fixation preference. Equal visual acuity (B) permits alternating fixation. Papilledema (D) and nystagmus (C) do not primarily produce unilateral fixation preference.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with vertical diplopia is asked to tilt the head toward each shoulder. Hypertropia increases on right head tilt. Which muscle is most likely paretic?","o":["Right superior oblique","Left superior oblique","Right lateral rectus","Left medial rectus","Right inferior rectus"],"a":0,"e":"The Bielschowsky head tilt test is used to identify superior oblique palsy. Hypertropia worsening on ipsilateral head tilt strongly indicates weakness of the superior oblique muscle on that side.<br><br>The superior oblique normally intorts and depresses the eye. Failure of these actions during head tilt causes vertical deviation to increase. This is a classic clinical examination scenario in orthoptic assessment.<br><br>Left superior oblique palsy (B) worsens on left tilt. Lateral rectus weakness (C) produces horizontal diplopia. Medial rectus palsy (D) affects adduction. Inferior rectus weakness (E) mainly impairs depression.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child suspected of having pseudostrabismus has broad epicanthal folds but symmetrical corneal light reflexes. What is the most likely diagnosis?","o":["True esotropia","Exotropia","Pseudostrabismus","Hypertropia","Duane syndrome"],"a":2,"e":"Pseudostrabismus commonly occurs in infants with broad epicanthal folds or flat nasal bridges, creating a false appearance of ocular deviation despite normal alignment. Symmetrical corneal reflexes confirm absence of true strabismus.<br><br>The Hirschberg test is extremely important in differentiating pseudostrabismus from genuine squint because unnecessary treatment can otherwise occur. Most children improve cosmetically with facial growth.<br><br>True esotropia (A) demonstrates asymmetrical reflexes and refixation movements. Exotropia (B) produces outward deviation. Hypertropia (D) causes vertical misalignment. Duane syndrome (E) involves globe retraction and motility limitation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with suspected restrictive strabismus undergoes forced duction testing. Resistance is encountered during passive abduction of the eye. What does this finding indicate?","o":["Mechanical restriction","Neurogenic palsy","Normal ocular motility","Optic nerve disease","Suppression"],"a":0,"e":"Forced duction testing assesses passive ocular movement and helps differentiate restrictive from paralytic strabismus. Resistance during attempted movement indicates mechanical restriction caused by fibrosis, entrapment, or thyroid eye disease.<br><br>The test is especially important before strabismus surgery because restrictive pathology requires different management compared with neurogenic muscle weakness. It is commonly performed under topical anesthesia. A positive forced duction test indicating mechanical restriction is a classic differentiating manoeuvre.<br><br>Neurogenic palsy (B) generally permits free passive movement. Normal motility (C) shows no resistance. Optic nerve disease (D) affects vision rather than passive motility. Suppression (E) is a sensory adaptation phenomenon.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child undergoing cover-uncover testing demonstrates no movement when one eye is covered, but inward refixation movement appears during alternate cover testing. What condition is present?","o":["Orthotropia","Manifest exotropia","Hypertropia","Esophoria","Nystagmus"],"a":3,"e":"Absence of movement on cover-uncover testing excludes manifest deviation, while inward refixation movement during alternate cover testing reveals latent outward drift controlled by fusion. This pattern indicates esophoria.<br><br>Alternate cover testing breaks binocular fusion completely, allowing latent deviations to appear. Detecting heterophorias is important in patients with headache, asthenopia, or intermittent diplopia.<br><br>Orthotropia (A) demonstrates no movement on either test. Manifest exotropia (B) appears on cover-uncover testing. Hypertropia (C) produces vertical movement. Nystagmus (E) causes oscillatory rather than corrective movement.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"During examination of ocular motility, a patient demonstrates limitation of abduction in the right eye with horizontal diplopia worse on right gaze. Which cranial nerve is most likely affected?","o":["Third cranial nerve","Fourth cranial nerve","Optic nerve","Sixth cranial nerve","Facial nerve"],"a":3,"e":"Sixth cranial nerve palsy weakens the lateral rectus muscle, causing impaired abduction and horizontal diplopia that worsens on gaze toward the affected side. Patients may adopt a compensatory head turn.<br><br>Examination of ocular motility remains one of the most important components of squint evaluation and cranial nerve assessment in ophthalmology clinics.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) causes ptosis and exotropia. Fourth nerve palsy (B) primarily produces vertical diplopia. Optic nerve lesions (C) impair vision. Facial nerve palsy (E) affects eyelid closure rather than ocular motility.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with intermittent exotropia undergoes Worth four-dot testing and reports seeing five lights. What does this finding indicate?","o":["Suppression","Normal fusion","Orthophoria","Amblyopia","Diplopia"],"a":4,"e":"Perception of five lights during Worth four-dot testing indicates diplopia because each eye perceives separate images simultaneously without fusion. The test helps evaluate binocular sensory status in strabismus patients.<br><br>Patients with intermittent exotropia may alternate between fusion, suppression, and diplopia depending on control of ocular alignment at the time of examination.<br><br>Suppression (A) results in fewer than four lights. Normal fusion (B) produces four lights. Amblyopia (D) reduces visual acuity rather than directly causing five-light perception. Orthophoria (C) demonstrates normal fusion findings.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with long-standing childhood squint demonstrates abnormal retinal correspondence on synoptophore examination. What does this finding represent?","o":["Retinal detachment","Corneal opacity","Optic nerve disease","Sensory adaptation to strabismus","Restrictive motility defect"],"a":3,"e":"Abnormal retinal correspondence is a cortical sensory adaptation in which the brain remaps corresponding retinal points to reduce diplopia and confusion in longstanding strabismus. It commonly develops in childhood deviations.<br><br>Detection of abnormal retinal correspondence is important before surgery because postoperative diplopia risk and binocular functional outcomes may be affected significantly. Synoptophore testing is frequently used for this purpose. Anomalous retinal correspondence in long-standing childhood squint is a classic sensory adaptation worth remembering.<br><br>Retinal detachment (A) affects retinal anatomy rather than sensory adaptation. Optic nerve disease (C) impairs visual transmission. Corneal opacity (B) reduces image clarity. Restrictive defects (E) involve mechanical motility limitation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"During squint examination, the examiner places an occluder over one eye while the patient fixates on a target. The uncovered eye is observed carefully for corrective movement. What is the primary purpose of the cover-uncover test?","o":["Measuring stereopsis","Evaluating color vision","Measuring corneal thickness","Assessing retinal function","Detecting manifest deviation"],"a":4,"e":"The cover-uncover test is specifically designed to detect manifest squint (tropia). When the fixing eye is covered, movement of the opposite eye to take up fixation indicates the presence of manifest ocular deviation.<br><br>This examination is fundamental in orthoptic assessment and is routinely performed in both pediatric and adult strabismus clinics. Careful observation of refixation movement determines the direction of deviation accurately.<br><br>Stereopsis (A) is assessed using Titmus testing. Corneal thickness (C) requires pachymetry. Retinal function (D) is evaluated by retinal investigations. Color vision (B) is assessed with Ishihara charts.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"While performing alternate cover testing, the examiner rapidly alternates the occluder between both eyes without allowing binocular fusion. What is the main purpose of this maneuver?","o":["Detecting latent deviation","Measuring intraocular pressure","Evaluating optic disc swelling","Assessing tear secretion","Detecting retinal detachment"],"a":0,"e":"Alternate cover testing disrupts binocular fusion completely, allowing latent ocular deviations (phorias) to become manifest temporarily. Corrective eye movement after shifting the occluder indicates the presence of heterophoria.<br><br>The test is especially useful in patients with asthenopia, intermittent diplopia, and binocular visual discomfort despite apparently normal ocular alignment during routine inspection.<br><br>Intraocular pressure (B) requires tonometry. Optic disc swelling (C) is evaluated by fundoscopy. Tear secretion (D) is assessed using Schirmer testing. Retinal detachment (E) requires retinal examination.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"During Hirschberg testing, the examiner shines a penlight toward the patient's eyes from approximately 50 cm away. What structure is primarily being evaluated in this test?","o":["Pupillary reflex pathway","Corneal light reflex alignment","Retinal vascular pattern","Lens transparency","Optic nerve function"],"a":1,"e":"The Hirschberg test evaluates ocular alignment by observing the position of the corneal light reflex relative to the center of the pupil in each eye. Asymmetry suggests ocular deviation.<br><br>This examination is particularly valuable in infants and poorly cooperative children because it provides rapid estimation of strabismus without requiring verbal responses or complex cooperation.<br><br>Pupillary pathways (A) are examined with light reflex testing. Retinal vessels (C) require fundoscopy. Lens transparency (D) is assessed by slit-lamp examination. Optic nerve function (E) involves visual acuity and field assessment.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient undergoing ocular motility examination is instructed to follow a target in the six cardinal positions of gaze. What is the principal purpose of this examination?","o":["Measuring refractive error","Evaluating corneal sensitivity","Assessing stereopsis","Measuring axial length","Evaluating extraocular muscle function"],"a":4,"e":"Examination in the six cardinal positions of gaze evaluates the function of individual extraocular muscles and identifies paralytic or restrictive ocular motility disorders. Limitation in a specific direction suggests weakness of the responsible muscle.<br><br>This assessment is a critical component of cranial nerve evaluation and strabismus examination in both emergency and outpatient ophthalmology settings.<br><br>Refractive error (A) requires refraction testing. Stereopsis (C) is evaluated separately. Axial length (D) requires biometry. Corneal sensitivity (B) is assessed using corneal aesthesiometry.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"During examination of a child with suspected squint, the examiner notes fixation preference by alternately covering each eye. What is the main clinical significance of fixation preference testing?","o":["Identifying amblyopia","Measuring corneal curvature","Detecting glaucoma","Evaluating retinal tears","Assessing lacrimal drainage"],"a":0,"e":"Fixation preference testing helps identify amblyopia in young children who cannot reliably perform formal visual acuity testing. Persistent use of one eye for fixation suggests reduced vision in the nonpreferred eye.<br><br>This method is especially valuable in preverbal children and forms an important part of pediatric squint examination during early visual development.<br><br>Glaucoma (C) requires pressure and optic nerve assessment. Corneal curvature (B) is measured by keratometry. Retinal tears (D) are evaluated fundoscopically. Lacrimal drainage (E) is assessed separately.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A 2-year-old child presents with constant inward deviation of both eyes since infancy. Examination shows cross-fixation and bilateral limitation of abduction that improves with doll's head maneuver. Which diagnosis is most likely?","o":["Duane syndrome","Congenital sixth nerve palsy","Brown syndrome","Infantile esotropia","Accommodative esotropia"],"a":3,"e":"Infantile esotropia typically presents before 6 months of age with large-angle constant esodeviation. Cross-fixation may simulate bilateral abduction deficit, but normal doll's head maneuver distinguishes it from true sixth nerve palsy.<br><br>The condition is strongly associated with latent nystagmus, inferior oblique overaction, and dissociated vertical deviation. Early surgical alignment improves binocular development and cosmetic outcomes.<br><br>Duane syndrome (A) shows globe retraction. Congenital sixth nerve palsy (B) demonstrates true abduction weakness. Brown syndrome (C) limits elevation in adduction. Accommodative esotropia (E) usually develops later in childhood.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with hypermetropia develops inward deviation while focusing on near objects. Cycloplegic refraction reveals +5 diopters in both eyes. Which treatment is most appropriate initially?","o":["Full hypermetropic correction","Botulinum toxin injection","Lateral rectus recession","Patching only","Prism therapy alone"],"a":0,"e":"Accommodative esotropia results from excessive accommodative convergence in hypermetropic children. Full cycloplegic hypermetropic correction reduces accommodative effort and therefore decreases convergent deviation significantly.<br><br>Most children demonstrate marked improvement or complete correction with spectacles alone. Early refractive correction also reduces amblyopia risk and promotes binocular visual development.<br><br>Lateral rectus recession (C) is surgical treatment reserved for residual deviation. Botulinum toxin (B) is not first-line therapy. Patching (D) treats amblyopia. Prism therapy (E) alone is insufficient.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with longstanding unilateral congenital cataract develops outward deviation of the affected eye. Which mechanism best explains this finding?","o":["Excessive accommodation","Retinal correspondence","Increased convergence","Superior oblique palsy","Loss of binocular fusion"],"a":4,"e":"Sensory exotropia develops when poor unilateral vision disrupts binocular fusion mechanisms. The affected eye gradually drifts outward because fusion can no longer maintain alignment.<br><br>Congenital cataract is a classic amblyogenic cause of sensory squint. Early cataract surgery and visual rehabilitation are essential to prevent irreversible amblyopia and sensory misalignment.<br><br>Accommodation excess (A) usually produces esotropia. Retinal correspondence (B) is an adaptive phenomenon. Superior oblique palsy (D) causes vertical deviation. Increased convergence (C) leads toward esodeviation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with left superior oblique palsy typically adopts which compensatory head posture?","o":["Head tilt to left side","Chin elevation","Head tilt to right side","Face turn to left","Chin depression"],"a":2,"e":"Patients with superior oblique palsy classically tilt the head away from the affected side to minimize vertical and torsional diplopia. Right head tilt compensates for left superior oblique weakness.<br><br>This compensatory posture reduces hypertropia and improves binocular single vision. Recognition of abnormal head posture is an important clinical clue during squint examination.<br><br>Head tilt toward the affected side (A) worsens hypertropia. Chin elevation (B) and depression (E) are less characteristic. Face turn (D) is more common in horizontal muscle palsies.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which muscle is primarily weakened in sixth cranial nerve palsy?","o":["Medial rectus","Inferior oblique","Superior rectus","Lateral rectus","Superior oblique"],"a":3,"e":"The sixth cranial nerve innervates the lateral rectus muscle, responsible for ocular abduction. Palsy therefore produces esotropia with inability to abduct the affected eye properly.<br><br>Patients commonly complain of horizontal diplopia worsening on gaze toward the affected side. Increased intracranial pressure is an important acquired cause in adults. Lateral rectus weakness causing an abduction deficit is the defining motor lesion of sixth nerve palsy.<br><br>Medial rectus (A) is supplied by the third nerve. Inferior oblique (B) and superior rectus (C) are also third nerve muscles. Superior oblique (E) is supplied by the fourth nerve.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"During cover testing, outward corrective movement occurs when the left eye is uncovered. What type of deviation is present?","o":["Left esotropia","Left exotropia","Right hypertropia","Orthophoria","Left hypotropia"],"a":0,"e":"Outward refixation movement indicates the eye was previously deviated inward. Therefore, outward movement on uncovering confirms esotropia in the affected eye.<br><br>Observation of corrective movement direction during cover testing is fundamental in diagnosing and classifying squint clinically.<br><br>Exotropia (B) produces inward movement on refixation. Hypertropia (C) and hypotropia (E) produce vertical movement. Orthophoria (D) shows no corrective movement.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with intermittent exotropia demonstrates normal binocular single vision between episodes of deviation. Which sensory function is preserved?","o":["Fusion and stereopsis","Suppression only","Monocular fixation only","Retinal detachment adaptation","Cycloplegia"],"a":0,"e":"Intermittent exotropia frequently preserves normal binocular fusion and stereopsis during periods of ocular alignment. Patients often maintain excellent depth perception in early stages of disease.<br><br>Loss of fusional control occurs intermittently, especially during fatigue or inattention. Preservation of stereopsis predicts better postoperative functional outcomes.<br><br>Suppression alone (B) does not indicate normal binocular vision. Monocular fixation (C) occurs in severe sensory imbalance. Retinal detachment adaptation (D) and cycloplegia (E) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which investigation is most appropriate for detecting suppression in a child with squint?","o":["Schirmer test","Gonioscopy","Keratometry","Worth four-dot test","Fluorescein angiography"],"a":3,"e":"Worth four-dot testing evaluates binocular fusion, diplopia, and suppression using red-green filters and illuminated targets. Suppression is a common sensory adaptation in childhood squint.<br><br>The test is simple, rapid, and widely used in orthoptic clinics. Children with longstanding deviation may suppress one eye to avoid diplopia and visual confusion.<br><br>Schirmer test (A) measures tear production. Keratometry (C) measures corneal curvature. Gonioscopy (B) evaluates anterior chamber angle anatomy. Angiography (E) studies retinal vessels.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with congenital ptosis develops esotropia and amblyopia. What is the most important mechanism responsible for amblyopia?","o":["Corneal edema","Optic neuritis","Increased accommodation","Visual deprivation","Cycloplegia"],"a":3,"e":"Severe congenital ptosis may obstruct the visual axis, causing deprivation amblyopia during critical visual development. Persistent visual deprivation may also contribute to secondary ocular misalignment.<br><br>Early recognition and timely surgical correction are essential to preserve visual development and prevent permanent amblyopia.<br><br>Corneal edema (A) is unrelated. Increased accommodation (C) contributes to accommodative esotropia. Optic neuritis (B) causes inflammatory visual loss. Cycloplegia (E) does not produce deprivation amblyopia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A child with esotropia develops dissociated vertical deviation. Which feature is characteristic of this condition?","o":["Downward drifting on occlusion","Inward drifting during fixation","Restricted abduction","Upward drifting of nonfixing eye","Torsional diplopia"],"a":3,"e":"Dissociated vertical deviation is characterized by spontaneous upward drifting of the nonfixing eye, especially during occlusion or visual inattention. It is strongly associated with infantile esotropia.<br><br>The condition represents abnormal supranuclear binocular control and may become cosmetically significant over time. Surgical treatment may be required in severe cases.<br><br>Downward drifting (A) is incorrect. Restricted abduction (C) suggests sixth nerve palsy. Torsional diplopia (E) is more typical of superior oblique palsy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with Duane retraction syndrome demonstrates globe retraction and narrowing of the palpebral fissure during adduction. Which muscle shows paradoxical innervation?","o":["Superior rectus","Medial rectus","Lateral rectus","Inferior oblique","Superior oblique"],"a":2,"e":"Duane retraction syndrome results from anomalous innervation of the lateral rectus muscle by fibers from the third cranial nerve. Simultaneous contraction of medial and lateral recti causes globe retraction.<br><br>The syndrome commonly presents with limited abduction and compensatory head posture. Globe retraction during adduction is the classic clinical clue.<br><br>Superior rectus (A), inferior oblique (D), and superior oblique (E) are not primarily involved. Medial rectus (B) contracts normally during adduction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"Which form of strabismus is most strongly associated with prematurity and neurological abnormalities?","o":["Infantile esotropia","Accommodative esotropia","Convergence insufficiency","Divergence excess exotropia","Cyclic exotropia"],"a":0,"e":"Infantile esotropia has increased association with prematurity, cerebral palsy, developmental delay, and perinatal neurological abnormalities. Large-angle constant esodeviation appears within the first six months of life.<br><br>Affected children frequently develop latent nystagmus, inferior oblique overaction, and dissociated vertical deviation during follow-up.<br><br>Accommodative esotropia (B) is linked with hypermetropia. Convergence insufficiency (C) affects near fixation. Divergence excess exotropia (D) mainly affects distance fixation. Cyclic exotropia (E) is uncommon.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which test is most useful for measuring stereopsis in children with intermittent exotropia?","o":["Titmus fly test","Hess chart","Maddox rod test","Schiotz tonometry","Bruckner test"],"a":0,"e":"The Titmus fly test evaluates stereopsis and binocular depth perception using polarized images. Children with intermittent exotropia often retain good stereopsis between episodes of ocular deviation.<br><br>Assessment of stereopsis is important because preserved binocular function predicts better visual and surgical outcomes.<br><br>Hess chart (B) evaluates muscle palsy. Maddox rod test (C) assesses diplopia. Schiotz tonometry (D) measures intraocular pressure. Bruckner test (E) screens for anisometropia and strabismus.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
{"q":"A patient with thyroid eye disease develops diplopia and limitation of elevation. Which clinical test best differentiates restrictive from paralytic pathology?","o":["Maddox wing test","Forced duction test","Worth four-dot test","Synoptophore","Titmus fly test"],"a":1,"e":"Forced duction testing differentiates restrictive strabismus from neurogenic palsy by assessing passive ocular movement. Resistance during passive movement indicates mechanical restriction.<br><br>In thyroid eye disease, fibrosis of extraocular muscles commonly causes restrictive motility defects requiring careful surgical planning.<br><br>Maddox wing (A) measures heterophoria. Worth four-dot testing (C) assesses suppression. Synoptophore (D) evaluates binocular sensory status. Titmus fly test (E) measures stereopsis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
{"q":"Which extraocular muscle overaction commonly develops secondarily in longstanding infantile esotropia?","o":["Superior rectus","Inferior rectus","Lateral rectus","Superior oblique","Inferior oblique"],"a":4,"e":"Inferior oblique overaction commonly develops in longstanding infantile esotropia and produces overelevation during adduction. The association is well recognized in pediatric strabismus practice.<br><br>The condition may become clinically significant and require simultaneous surgical weakening during esotropia correction procedures. Inferior oblique overaction developing secondary to superior oblique palsy is a classic compensatory pattern.<br><br>Superior rectus (A) and inferior rectus (B) dysfunction mainly cause vertical deviation. Lateral rectus (C) weakness produces esotropia. Superior oblique (D) palsy produces torsional and vertical abnormalities.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
];